Last July my grandma (who is pretty much my mom) was rushed to the ER because of stomach pain. She had to go into emergency surgery and had her gallbladder removed, and some of her liver. She was diagnosed with stage 2/ almost 3 pancreatic cancer, she has masses all over her liver and organs surrounding it. A few months later they found masses on her lungs, and in both breast (she had to have both of them removed). Right now she's taking radiation pills, and has to go to chemo (she has a port in her chest for her chemo) its been really hard and i can't imagine what she's going through, but i just keep praying and have faith in God it'll all be okay.
Im so glad you're okay Alex!
We'll all keep praying for you. ❤

snippet.textDisplay: Thank you Alex Trebek for sharing your story so candidly and with so much grace for the world to see. I am reminded of my mother who fought kidney failure from diabetic complications for three years. It was a hard fight too, with so much pain and difficult moments, receiving diálisis three times a week. And at times, like you, she wanted to give up. But like she’d pull through because of us, her family and loved ones. And I thank her for that because despite the pain, those three years continued to give us beautiful memories, love from her, and even words of wisdom and encouragement from her when we needed them as we struggled to face life ourselves. So thank you Alex for being also an inspiration. I wish you well!

snippet.textDisplay: Lost my dad to lung cancer in 2011. It was a horrifyingly dark road to be on, they found it at stage 4. He lasted only 10 months after his diagnosis. It’s devastating, it’s scary, it truly is a living nightmare. I was his caregiver for those 10 months and over that time I watched him completely break down and lose who he was during his fight - he was 63. I can very vividly remember how real it all was, week after week going to see doctors and the chemotherapy - it was just more reassuring that his time was up, and up very soon. Cancer is terrible - it took my father and drained the life out of me for a while after he died - he left this earth the day after my 30th birthday - 2011 was not the most fun year. But as hard as it was - I’ll never forget him and how hard he fought. Though it was a rough 10 months, he was a hell of a trooper and I can only envy his will to fight for as long as he could. Love you dad - Robert George Brozic; 7/14/48 - 12/6/11 - Rest In Peace..... 🙏

snippet.textDisplay:
When cancer drags you down, it drags you down LITERALLY. I work with the elderly/disabled and seeing their life through my eyes makes me wish that just because you’re ill and disabled doesn’t mean you should stop your life and recluse. Yes, you should rest when you need to but not lay in bed all day when depression hits.

Anyway, Thank you, Alex. For being constant. For keeping a positive attitude with the will to keep living. I’m really hoping for you to continue to be with us for as long as God will keep you here. :)
